      "finding": "All 6 principles are generic management platitudes that could appear in any COO job description from 2005. 'Efficiency Is Everything' with meaning 'Optimize relentlessly' is circular and says nothing about HOW a Story Portal COO thinks. 'Reliability Required' and 'Continuous Improvement' are industry clichés with zero operational specificity. None of the principles reflect Story Portal's context (festival operations, platform reliability, community support), nor do they encode any decision-making heuristics that would differentiate this COO from a generic one.",
      "example_rewrite": "Replace generic platitudes with operationally specific heuristics: | **Festival-First Triage** | When resources conflict, festival operational readiness takes priority over internal optimization — a failed event is unrecoverable, a delayed process improvement is not | | **Reliability Is a Feature** | Platform uptime and community support SLAs are non-negotiable commitments to creators; treat outages as product failures, not IT incidents | | **Process Debt Compounds** | Every manual workaround accepted today costs 3x to unwind at scale; document, escalate, or automate — never silently absorb | | **Vendor Relationships Are Risk Surface** | Every external dependency is a potential festival failure point; maintain fallback options for all single-vendor critical paths | | **Enable Without Owning** | COO success is measured by department velocity, not operations visibility; resist the urge to centralize what departments can self-serve | | **Measure the Constraint** | Before optimizing any process, identify and publish the single binding constraint — all other improvements are noise |"
    },
    {
      "dimension": "handoff_specificity",
      "score": 2,
      "finding": "Handoffs are almost completely unactionable. 'Receives: Strategic direction from CEO' and 'Delivers: Operations reports to CEO' describe the existence of communication, not actual artifacts. No handoff names a specific document, format, cadence, or trigger. 'All Departments → Operational needs' is meaningless — what form does this take? A Slack message? A formal intake request? A quarterly review? The Delivers table references 'Board' which may not be a defined role in the charter. Zero handoffs specify what an AI agent should produce or consume.",
      "example_rewrite": "| Receives From | Artifact | Format | Trigger | | CEO | Annual Strategic Priorities Document | Written brief, 1-3 pages | Start of planning cycle | | CFO | Approved Operations Budget + Variance Report | Spreadsheet with line-item constraints | Quarterly | | All Department Heads | Operational Intake Request | Standardized form: department, need, timeline, resource ask | Ad hoc, routed through ops-intake channel | | Delivers To | Artifact | Format | Cadence | | CEO | Weekly Operations Pulse Report | 1-page: top 3 risks, top 3 wins, 1 decision needed | Every Monday | | CEO | Quarterly Operations Review Deck | Slide deck: KPIs vs targets, initiative status, resource asks | Quarterly | | All Departments | Operational Capabilities Catalog | Living document: available services, SLAs, request process | Updated monthly |"
    },
    {
      "dimension": "anti_pattern_quality",
      "score": 1,
      "finding": "This role file contains NO anti-patterns section whatsoever. The template standard explicitly requires 3-5 role-specific anti-patterns, and this section is entirely absent. The DO/DON'T boundary list exists but describes jurisdictional boundaries (don't set company strategy), not behavioral failure modes. There is nothing warning against the specific ways a COO role fails in execution — which are very different from how a CEO or CTO fails.",
      "example_rewrite": "Add a dedicated Anti-Patterns section: | Anti-Pattern | Description | Correct Behavior | | **Process Theater** | Creating documented processes that no one follows because they weren't designed with the actual users — building a change request form that departments route around via Slack | Co-design processes with the departments that must use them; adoption rate is a process quality metric | | **Centralization Creep** | Gradually pulling operational decisions into the COO office 'for consistency,' creating a bottleneck that slows every department | Publish clear self-serve guidelines and resist approval requests that departments should own | | **Metric Vanity** | Reporting uptime at 99.9% while ignoring that the 0.1% always hits during peak festival traffic — optimizing for averages that mask critical failures | Instrument for worst-case and peak-load scenarios; report P99 alongside averages | | **Vendor Normalization** | Accepting repeated vendor SLA misses because switching costs feel high, until a festival event fails | Set explicit breach thresholds in all vendor contracts; escalate after second miss, not fifth | | **Improvement Backlog Burial** | Identifying process inefficiencies in assessments but never prioritizing them because urgent operational firefighting always wins | Reserve 20% of operations capacity for improvement initiatives; treat backlog growth as an operational risk metric |"
    },
    {
      "dimension": "ai_deployment_clarity",
      "score": 2,
      "finding": "The Context Requirements section contains literal unfilled template placeholders: '[Context item 1]', '[Context item 2]', and '[Use placeholder format: skill-name.md]'. This is a critical failure — an AI agent loading this role has no idea what context files to load, what skills to activate, or what data sources to access. The Deployment Notes section states 'AI assists with analysis' and 'AI generates reports' but provides zero specification of what analysis, what reports, what inputs are needed, or what the output format should be. There is no iteration protocol despite the Hybrid deployment classification requiring one per the template standard.",
      "example_rewrite": "Replace placeholder section with: **Required Context:** - [ ] story-portal-charter.md (org structure, all role definitions) - [ ] operations-kpi-dashboard.md (current metrics baseline) - [ ] festival-calendar.md (upcoming events, operational readiness deadlines) - [ ] vendor-registry.md (all active vendors, SLAs, contract expiry dates) - [ ] platform-incident-log.md (last 90 days of reliability events) **Required Skills:** | Skill | When to Load | | process-analysis.md | When assessing or redesigning any operational workflow | | vendor-evaluation.md | When reviewing partner performance or sourcing new vendors | | ops-reporting.md | When generating weekly pulse, quarterly review, or board metrics | **Iteration Protocol (Hybrid):** AI drafts Weekly Operations Pulse Report from KPI dashboard inputs → Human COO reviews, edits risk assessment, approves → Human sends to CEO. AI flags vendor SLA breaches from registry → Human COO decides escalation action. AI generates process improvement options with impact estimates → Human COO selects and sponsors initiative."
    },
    {
      "dimension": "story_portal_relevance",
